<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,324,549,575]" box="[189,324,549,575]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,549,575]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,549,575]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[189,1398,596,657]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[640,774,596,622]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplistylus">
<emphasis box="[640,774,596,622]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">amplistylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘large stylus’ and referring to the enlarged left-side surstylus. The name is a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
